Exercise 2

The answers for this exercise are already provided to help guide you. Clean up the narrative to reflect what you want to submit. Lets break it into steps:

First, lets plot the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Next, lets calculate the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645
  1. The datasaurus_dozen dataframe that contains 13 datasets, we first use filter to find the rows where dataset = dino_data and saved them in a new data frame called dino_data.
  2. We used ggplot to create a scatterplot of the x and y variabels from the dino_data data frame.
  3. We used cor (x, y) to calculate the Pearson correlation between x and y variables in dino_data. We assigned the correlation we calculated to a variable named r and presented the correlation in a tibble.

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~dataset, ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

1.We used ggplot to create scatterplots of x and y for all datasets in datasaurus_dozen. The data are faceted by dataset, so that each dataset appears in its own panel.

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y)) %>%
  print(13, width = Inf)
## # A tibble: 13  2
##    dataset          r
##    <chr>        <dbl>
##  1 away       -0.0641
##  2 bullseye   -0.0686
##  3 circle     -0.0683
##  4 dino       -0.0645
##  5 dots       -0.0603
##  6 h_lines    -0.0617
##  7 high_lines -0.0685
##  8 slant_down -0.0690
##  9 slant_up   -0.0686
## 10 star       -0.0630
## 11 v_lines    -0.0694
## 12 wide_lines -0.0666
## 13 x_shape    -0.0656
  1. We calculate the Pearson correlation between x and y for each dataset. We used groupby to group the data by the dataset variable. As we can see the printed tibble, the correlations are very similar across the 13 different data frames, although their plots were very different.
